        <image source="images/exponential-stretch-horizontal" width="50%" >
            <shortdescription>Graph of both curves in table above showing the horizontal stretch</shortdescription>
            <description>
                <p>The horizontal axis ranges from -16 to 16. Notice that this is 4 time wider than the previous examples. The vertical axis ranges from 0 to above 16. Tick marks on the vertical axis are each double the one below beginning at 1.</p>
                <p>The points for both curves from the table above are plotted and graphs of the curves are sketched through them. For each of the points on <m>y=2^x</m> there is a corresponding point on <m>y=2^(0.25x)</m>.</p>
                <p>There is a horizontal arrow starting at <m>(-1,\frac{1}{2})</m> on the curve <m>y=2^x</m> that stretches to <m>(-4,\frac{1}{2})</m> on the curve <m>y=2^{0.25x}</m>. There is another horizontal arrow starting at <m>(1,2)</m> on the curve <m>y=2^x</m> that stretches to <m>(4,2)</m> on the curve <m>y=2^{0.25x}</m>. These arrows illustrate how points on <m>y=2^x</m> have a corresponding point on <m>y=2^{0.25x}</m> which is 4 times as far away from the y-axis. This is why the horizontal axis is 4 times wider than previous examples.</p>
